{"id":"2205.06070","submitter":"Margaret Reid","authors":"M D Reid and P D Drummond","title":"A quantum phase-space equivalence leads to hidden causal loops in a\n  model for measurement consistent with macroscopic realism","comments":"Third version modified for clearer explanations and with typos\n  corrected","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph gr-qc math-ph math.MP","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We show how unobservable causal loops arise from quantum mechanics, and can\nexplain quantum measurement consistently with macroscopic realism. We analyze a\nmeasurement $\\hat{x}$ on a system prepared in a superposition of eigenstates\n$|x_{j}\\rangle$ where the measurement is modeled by amplification. We prove an\nequivalence between the positive phase-space distribution $Q(x,p,t)$, and\nsimultaneous backward and forward-propagating stochastic trajectories for\namplitudes $x$ and $p$. The sampling for the amplified variable $x$ is\nspecified by a future boundary condition determined by the measurement setting,\nthe backward and forward trajectories being linked at the initial-time boundary\nto form a loop. We confirm that the joint densities for $x(t)$ and $p(t)$ yield\n$Q(x,p,t)$, thus demonstrating causal consistency and Born's rule. A feature is\nhidden vacuum noise associated with an eigenstate. Unlike the eigenvalue\n$x_{j}$, this noise is not amplified, the fluctuations originating from future\nboundary conditions. For macroscopic superpositions of $|x_{j}\\rangle$, we show\nconsistency with macroscopic realism: the outcome for $\\hat{x}$ can be\nconsidered a real property at the time $t_{0}$ prior to measurement\n(independent of future events). We deduce a hybrid causal structure involving\ncausal relations for amplified variables, along with hidden causal loops for\nunamplified quantities, demonstrating that causal loops do not imply\n(observable) retrocausality. Further, we evaluate $Q_{j}(x,p,0)$ for the\ntrajectories conditioned on the outcome $x_{j}$. The ``state'' defined by this\nfunction cannot be a quantum state, the uncertainties for $\\hat{x}$ and\n$\\hat{p}$ being too small. However, $Q_{j}(x,p,0)$ approaches that of\n$|x_{j}\\rangle$ for a macroscopic superposition. Our results provide a\nframework for study of Einstein-Podolsky-Rosen and Bell correlations.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 12 May 2022 13:10:20 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Sat, 6 Aug 2022 09:12:24 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Mon, 6 Mar 2023 10:22:36 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-03-07"}
